      <h2>What Is the Great Wave off Kanagawa?</h2>
      <p><em>The Great Wave off Kanagawa</em> (神奈川沖浪裏, <em>Kanagawa-oki nami-ura</em>) is a woodblock print by the Japanese artist <strong>Katsushika Hokusai</strong>, created around <strong>1831</strong> as part of his series <em>Thirty-Six Views of Mount Fuji</em>. It depicts a towering wave with claw-like cresting foam about to crash over fishing boats, with Mount Fuji small and calm in the background. The original print is held in major collections including The Met and the British Museum, and remains one of the most recognized images in the world.<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Great_Wave_off_Kanagawa" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent-400 hover:underline">[Source: Wikipedia — The Great Wave off Kanagawa]</a> Hokusai's broader life and ukiyo-e legacy are documented in standard art-history references such as <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Hokusai" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent-400 hover:underline">Britannica's Hokusai entry</a>.</p>

      <h2>Great Wave Tattoo Meaning</h2>
      <p>When people search for the <strong>great wave tattoo meaning</strong>, they're usually looking for what the design says about the wearer. The most common readings:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Resilience and perseverance</strong> — the small boats survive a massive force, a metaphor for pushing through hardship.</li>
        <li><strong>Respect for nature's power</strong> — the wave dwarfs Mount Fuji, reminding us we are small against the natural world.</li>
        <li><strong>Overcoming adversity</strong> — the moment captured is one of peak danger and imminent relief; many wearers mark a personal storm they've weathered.</li>
        <li><strong>Strength in transition</strong> — waves are constant motion, a symbol for change, flow, and moving forward.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Kanagawa Tattoo Meaning</h2>
      <p>The word <strong>Kanagawa</strong> is the coastal prefecture south of Tokyo where Hokusai set the scene. A <strong>Kanagawa tattoo</strong> therefore carries the same symbolism as the great wave, but with an explicit nod to its Japanese origin and place. Wearers who choose "Kanagawa" specifically often want to honor Japanese art history or a personal connection to the region rather than a generic ocean wave.</p>

      <h2>Hokusai Wave Tattoo Meaning</h2>
      <p>A <strong>Hokusai wave tattoo</strong> points to the artist himself. Choosing this framing signals appreciation for <em>ukiyo-e</em> (Japanese woodblock print culture) and the lineage of artists who turned everyday scenes into timeless symbols. It's a popular choice for people who see tattoos as art history worn on the body — and it pairs naturally with other Japanese iconography like koi, dragons, or Mt. Fuji.</p>

      <h2>Design Ideas &amp; Placement</h2>
      <p>The composition scales well across the body:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Full sleeve or back piece</strong> — the classic Irezumi approach, with the wave as the centerpiece and clouds, Fuji, or a koi woven in.</li>
        <li><strong>Forearm or calf</strong> — a single cresting wave reads clean in black-and-grey or with a limited blue palette true to the print.</li>
        <li><strong>Minimalist version</strong> — just the claw-like foam line in fine line work for a subtle, modern take.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Color choice matters: a <em>blue-and-white</em> palette stays faithful to Hokusai's print, while a full-color Japanese sleeve leans traditional. Talk to your artist about which reads best on your skin tone and placement.</p>

      <h2>Is a Great Wave Tattoo Cultural Appropriation?</h2>
      <p>This is a fair question. Traditional Japanese tattooing (<em>Irezumi</em>) has complex cultural history, including periods when it was associated with outlaws. Most contemporary Japanese tattoo artists welcome appreciation of the art form when it's done with respect — working with a knowledgeable artist, learning the symbolism, and not stripping the imagery of its meaning. If you're unsure, ask your artist and read about the history before committing.</p>

